### Describe the bug

I'm not sure if this is a bug, but I want to at least leave a breadcrumb in case any visitors from the future are experiencing this problem. May not be worth your time to debug, as the workaround (follow the demo instructions more closely) is straightforward.

The graphql client / auth exchange of our react-native app (expo sdk 45, babel 7.18) are fairly close to the vanilla setup in the docs (it's that "fairly" that lost me two days debugging this)

Depending on how I merge the new headers into the `addAuthToOperation` operation, the app will work normally for most queries but will never return from mutations, and will show odd behavior the second and further times certain queries are fetched (the operations are never torn down)

What it comes down to is that using lodash `_.merge`, which does a deep copy of the context, breaks urql, despite the enumerable properties of both results being identical. I don't know if we're disturbing object reference equality, or handing over something that's being modified in place, or unwittingly modifying something in place that we oughtn't.

Toggling between the following two changes breaks/ fixes:

### Bad version:

in graphql client setup (same static BaseHeaders bag is handed over each time):

```javascript
  const graphqlClient = Urql.createClient({
   // .... other setup
    fetchOptions: () => {
        return { redirect: 'follow', headers: BaseHeaders }
    },
}
```

In addAuthToOperation, non-modifying version of lodash merge does a deep merge of the new and old contexts:

```javascript
    addAuthToOperation({ authState, operation }) {
      if ((! authState?.token)) { return operation }
      //
      const fetchOptions = authFetchOptions(operation)
      fetchOptions.headers = { ...fetchOptions.headers, ...getHeaders(authState) }
      const newContext = _.merge({}, operation.context, { fetchOptions })
      return Urql.makeOperation(operation.kind, operation, newContext)
    },
```

### Works:

in graphql client setup (copy of base headers is sent each time)

```javascript
  const graphqlClient = Urql.createClient({
   // .... other setup
    fetchOptions: () => {
        return { redirect: 'follow', headers: { ...BaseHeaders } }
    },
}
```

```javascript
    addAuthToOperation({ authState, operation }) {
      try {
        if ((! authState?.token)) { return operation /* not logged in */ }
        //
        const fetchOptions   = authFetchOptions(operation)
        fetchOptions.headers = { ...fetchOptions.headers, ...getHeaders(authState) }
        const context = { ...operation.context, fetchOptions }
        const newOp = Urql.makeOperation(operation.kind, operation, context)
        return newOp
      } catch (err) {
        Log.error(err, { act: 'willAuthError' })
        return operation
      }
    },
```






