### Describe the bug

As the title states, if I do something like:

```typescript
const client = createClient({
  url: "abc123obviouslyfakeurltotriggererror",
  requestPolicy: "network-only",
  fetchOptions: {},
  exchanges: [
    ...defaultExchanges,
    errorExchange({
      onError(error) {
        console.log("custom error example #2: hello world");
      }
    })
  ]
});
```

I notice that my `errorExchange` callback does not fire. However, when I explicitly define all exchanges, `errorExchange` works:

```typescript
const client = createClient({
  url: "abc123obviouslyfakeurltotriggererror",
  requestPolicy: "network-only",
  fetchOptions: {},
  exchanges: [
    dedupExchange,
    cacheExchange,
    errorExchange({
      onError(error) {
        console.log("custom error example #1: hello world");
      }
    }),
    fetchExchange
  ]
});
```

Is this a "feature", or a bug 😄 ? I would have expected that when defining `errorExchange` _after_ `defaultExchanges`, that my custom `errorExchange` would be used. Though my guess is with the internals, since it is an array, it is difficult (or maybe even impossible to detect multiple instances of `errorExchange`, and thus when using `defaultExchanges`, the first (i.e. default) `errorExchange` is taken instead of a custom defined one.

Fiddling around with the `urql` version in codesandbox, I can confirm this "bug" affects versions 2.2.2 and up (to the current, 3.0.3) 

